         <abstract>
            <p>For a number of years the price-future earnings ratio has been used as a tool in judging relative values among common stocks having different rates of growth. In this article a ramification of the "years to earn price" concept has been integrated with another device designed to improve valuations by compensating for prevailing long-term interest rates. When applied to electric utility common stocks, the two mechanisms afford a logical method of measuring the growth rate anticipated by the market place itself for an individual utility's future per share earnings trend. Comparison of the market's appraisal of future growth against reliable analytical projections should assist equity managers in reaching decisions involving portfolio changes.</p>
          </abstract>
